File Permissions & Ownership Lab (Core Linux Skill)

This is critical for:

Cloud security

AWS / Azure IAM concepts

Server access control

🎯 Objective

You will learn:

How Linux controls access to files

How to read permissions

How to modify permissions safely

How ownership works

🧠 Step 1 — Understand Permissions

Run:

ls -l

Example output:

-rw-rw-r-- 1 nambia-mangare nambia-mangare 2176 Mar 1 notes.txt
Break it down:
-rw-rw-r--
│ │ │ │
│ │ │ └── Others permissions
│ │ └──── Group permissions
│ └────── Owner permissions
└──────── File type
🔑 Meaning of symbols
Symbol	Meaning
r	read
w	write
x	execute
-	no permission
🧪 Step 2 — Create Practice Environment
cd ~/ubuntu-linux-basics/linux-practice
mkdir permissions-lab
cd permissions-lab

touch file1.txt
touch file2.txt

Check:

ls -l
🔐 Step 3 — Change Permissions (chmod)
Remove all permissions:
chmod 000 file1.txt

Check:

ls -l

👉 You should see:

---------- file1.txt

Now try:

cat file1.txt

❌ You will get Permission denied

Give full permissions:
chmod 777 file1.txt

Now:

ls -l
-rwxrwxrwx file1.txt
⚠️ Important Concept
Permission	Meaning
777	full access (not secure)
755	common for scripts
644	common for files
🧪 Step 4 — Use Secure Permissions
chmod 644 file2.txt

Check:

ls -l
👤 Step 5 — Ownership (chown)

Check owner:

ls -l

Change owner (requires sudo):

sudo chown root:root file1.txt

Check:

ls -l

👉 Owner should now be root

🧠 Step 6 — Why This Matters

This is exactly how:

Servers restrict access

Logs are protected

Sensitive files are secured

Cloud permissions work (similar concept to IAM)

🧪 Mini Challenge

Create a file:

touch secure-data.txt

Set permissions so:

Only YOU can read/write

No one else can access

👉 Expected command:

chmod 600 secure-data.txt
