🔥 What You Just Learned

You now understand:

File security in Linux

Permission structures

Ownership control

How systems enforce access

This is directly used in cloud security roles.

chmod 600 file.txt means:

Owner (you) → can read & write (rw-)

Group → no permissions (---)

Others → no permissions (---)

So only you can access the file, making it private and secure.

Example ls -l output:

-rw------- 1 nambia-mangare nambia-mangare 0 Mar 20 12:00 file.txt

The dashes after the first rw indicate no permissions for group or others.

This is the standard way to protect sensitive files in Linux.
Let’s move to the Processes & System Monitoring Lab — a core skill for mastering Linux and understanding how the system works.

Linux Processes & System Monitoring Lab
Objective

Learn how to view running processes

Understand CPU and memory usage

Manage processes safely (stop, kill, inspect)

Document exercises in GitHub

Step 1 — Check running processes
ps

Shows processes running in the current terminal session

Output example:

  PID TTY          TIME CMD
 1234 pts/0    00:00:00 bash
 5678 pts/0    00:00:01 top

Explanation:

PID → Process ID

TTY → Terminal the process is attached to

TIME → CPU time used

CMD → Command that started the process

Step 2 — See all processes
ps aux

Shows all running processes

Useful for seeing system-wide activity

Columns:

USER → who started the process

PID → process ID

%CPU / %MEM → resource usage

COMMAND → what is running

Step 3 — Monitor processes live
top

Opens live process monitor

Shows CPU, memory, processes

Use q to quit

Optional: try htop if installed (better visual):

sudo apt install htop
htop
Step 4 — Find a process by name
ps aux | grep bash

Filters processes containing “bash”

Useful to locate specific programs

Step 5 — Stop a process

First, find its PID:

ps aux | grep firefox

Then terminate it safely:

kill PID

If it refuses, force kill:

kill -9 PID

⚠️ Use force only if needed; safe practice first.

Step 6 — Check system load
uptime

Shows how long system has been running

Load averages for 1, 5, 15 minutes

df -h

Shows disk usage

free -h

Shows memory usage
Let’s move on to the Linux Networking Commands Lab — essential for cloud, DevOps, and security work.

Linux Networking Commands Lab
Objective

Understand basic network commands

Test connectivity and network configuration

Document exercises in GitHub

Step 1 — Check your IP address
ip a

or older version:

ifconfig

Explanation:

Shows IP address, subnet, and network interface status

Example output snippet:

2: enp0s3: <BROADCAST,MULTICAST,UP,LOWER_UP> mtu 1500
    inet 192.168.1.10/24 brd 192.168.1.255 scope global dynamic enp0s3

inet → your IPv4 address

enp0s3 → interface name

Step 2 — Test connectivity

Ping a host:

ping google.com -c 4

-c 4 → send 4 packets

Output shows response time for each packet

Step 3 — Check routing table
route -n

or modern:

ip route

Shows default gateway and routing paths

Step 4 — Check network services
netstat -tulnp

or modern:

ss -tulnp

Shows active TCP/UDP listening ports

Useful for troubleshooting services

Step 5 — Test external connectivity
curl -I https://www.google.com

Returns HTTP headers from the server

Confirms internet connection and server response

Step 6 — Trace route
traceroute google.com

Shows the path packets take to reach a host

Helps identify network bottlenecks

Step 7 — DNS lookup
nslookup google.com

Shows IP addresses associated with a domain

Useful for troubleshooting DNS issues
